            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Raymond Wen\u2019s San Francisco story began not with him, but with the scent of his parents' laundromat in the Richmond District. The second-generation son of immigrants from Guangdong, Raymond grew up folding other people\u2019s clothes, his childhood measured in the hum of dryers and the hiss of steam presses. School was a means to an end; he was a practical, observant kid, more interested in how the Muni buses navigated the city's steep hills than in algebra. He graduated from George Washington High School with a diploma but no clear direction.\n\nFor a few years, he drifted through stockroom jobs and delivery gigs, watching the first dot-com boom transform his hometown from a distance. The world of startups felt alien. What he craved was stability, the kind his parents had built through tireless work. The turning point came in his late twenties when an uncle suggested he take the Muni operator\u2019s exam. It promised a union wage, a pension, and a tangible role in the city he knew so intimately. He passed.\n\nFor the last 25 years, Raymond\u2019s office has been the driver\u2019s seat of a city bus, most often the 38-Geary line. He\u2019s a fixture, a quiet observer of the city\u2019s daily opera. He met his wife, Mei, a nursing assistant, when she was a regular on his route. Together, they saved enough to buy a modest home in the Outer Sunset years ago, a foggy refuge from the city\u2019s frantic energy.\n\nHis 6.8-mile morning commute in his Camry is a quiet ritual before the chaos. From behind the wheel of his bus, he sees everything: the unhoused seeking warmth, the tourists with their maps, the tech workers with their headphones, the families he\u2019s watched grow up. He has a small circle of fellow drivers he plays mahjong with, but his world is centered on Mei and their daughter, who is now studying at UC Davis. His greatest pride is that she has opportunities he never did. His hopes are simple: see his daughter thrive, retire comfortably with Mei, and maybe take a road trip to the national parks. He is the city\u2019s circulatory system, a man who doesn\u2019t code its future but ensures it keeps moving, one stop at a time."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers being ten, watching his father\u2019s hands, rough and calloused, expertly folding a warm, crisp sheet in the laundromat. The air was thick with the scent of bleach and steam. In that moment, he didn\u2019t just see a chore; he saw a quiet dignity, a relentless dedication to providing for his family. He learned then that true value wasn't loud or celebrated, but found in the steady, reliable work of one\u2019s hands. It was a lesson he carried with him always.\n\n2.\nHis first solo run on the 38-Geary. His knuckles were white on the enormous steering wheel, and every lurch and hiss of the air brakes felt monumental. As he pulled away from the curb at Geary and 48th, he saw his reflection in the rearview mirror. He wasn't just Raymond Wen anymore; he was Operator Wen. For the first time, he felt like an essential part of the city's machinery, not just a spectator. The feeling was both terrifying and deeply satisfying.\n\n3.\nShe used to get on his bus at Masonic, always with a tired smile after her nursing shift. One rainy afternoon, Mei dropped her transit pass and, flustered, just laughed a genuine, unselfconscious laugh. That sound cut right through the drone of the engine and the gloom outside. It was the first time he felt the bus wasn\u2019t just his job, but the place where his own life was actually beginning. That simple, bright moment changed the entire landscape of his route.\n\n4.\nThe day they got the keys to the Outer Sunset house, he and Mei stood in the empty living room as the fog rolled in, muffling the world. He could smell the faint salt of the nearby ocean. After years of driving through the city's symphony of noise, this profound quiet felt like the ultimate luxury. He squeezed Mei\u2019s hand, feeling the solid floor beneath his feet. This wasn\u2019t just a house; it was an anchor, a quiet harbor they had built together, one fare at a time.\n\n5.\nHe remembers standing on the curb as his daughter loaded the last box into her car for UC Davis. She hugged him tight, smelling of the same laundry detergent from his childhood. As she drove away, a wave of pride so fierce it almost buckled his knees washed over him. All the early mornings, the long shifts, the endless river of faces on Geary\u2014it all led to this. His daughter was driving toward a future he had only dreamed of, on a road paved by his own steady route."
